    2. http://www.signal-spam.fr/en/index.php/frontend


+--------------------------------------------------------------------+
| 'Virus Sponge' Could Improve Flu Treatments, Diabetes Care, Vaccine|
|   from the many-pegs-in-many-holes dept.                           |
|   posted by ScuttleMonkey on Sunday May 13, @11:22 (Biotech)       |
|   http://science.slashdot.org/article.pl?sid=07/05/13/1413249      |
+--------------------------------------------------------------------+

University of Maryland researchers have announced a new "[0]virus sponge"
that could aid in the treatment of, among other things, avian flu. The
sponge woks similar to kidney dialysis, filtering the harmful virus from
the blood. "The virus sponge is based on a technology called molecular
imprinting. In molecular imprinting, researchers stamp a molecule's shape
into a substance (in this case, a hydrogel--a sponge-like material). When
the specific molecule filters through the hydrogel, it fits in the
imprint hole and is trapped."

Discuss this story at:
    http://science.slashdot.org/comments.pl?sid=07/05/13/1413249

Links:
    0. http://www.sciencedaily.com/releases/2007/05/070513083222.htm


+--------------------------------------------------------------------+
| Rethinking the Linux Distribution?                                 |
|   from the pc-to-mainframe-and-back-again dept.                    |
|   posted by ScuttleMonkey on Sunday May 13, @12:31 (Operating Syste|
|   http://linux.slashdot.org/article.pl?sid=07/05/13/1441227        |
+--------------------------------------------------------------------+

[0]eldavojohn writes "ONLamp.com is running an interesting article about
[1]rethinking how the community distributes Linux and the open source
applications that often come with Linux. The author isn't arguing that
Linux needs to become a full blown web OS over night but instead, asking
if the community should be considering 'Software as a Service' and what
he means by that is perhaps many of the open source applications that run
on Linux should be available through a browser. The reasons for this are
obvious, the code is open so anyone could host it, it would be platform
independent so anyone could use it and it might attract more users to the
Linux environment. The obvious note here is that many of the enterprise
software makers are switching to Software as a Service, shouldn't the
open source community investigate the possibility of a Web OS?"

Discuss this story at:
    http://linux.slashdot.org/comments.pl?sid=07/05/13/1441227

Links:
    0. mailto:djohnsop@gmu.edu
    1. http://www.onlamp.com/pub/a/onlamp/2007/05/10/rethinking-the-linux-distribution.html?page=1


